				\begin{document}$$\epsilon$$\end{document}ϵ, provides a powerful and quantitative method for characterizing electric propulsion plume divergence and evolution. If used properly, emittance, which is a beam parallelism measure from the particle accelerator community [27–32, 42, 43], can be used in the near-thruster region to characterize the impacts of inter- and intra-species collisions in the plume as well as expansion and propagation behavior in the vacuum facility and spacecraft environments. Accelerator beams such as the Large Hadron Collider (LHC) at CERN propagate within confining systems for kilometers [44], orders of magnitude longer distances than the beams and plumes produced by electric propulsion systems which propagate relatively short distances within the thruster, mm to cm, and order of meters within a test facility or spacecraft environment. In pursuit of keeping charged particle beams steady and confined for such long distances, the particle accelerator research community has developed a rich literature of beam quality analysis and diagnostic metrics [27–32, 42, 43]. Emittance is one such beam quality metric, which displays the influence of non-Hamiltonian forces on the beam. Emittance plots convey a transverse particle position component against the same component of transverse angle, where angle in this context [27–32, 42, 43] is defined as the ratio of momentum in the transverse direction to momentum in the axial direction of beam propagation,7\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
